<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1845,1872]" pageId="2" pageNumber="78">Comments</emphasis>
. This species does not seem to be attracted by light, but was only found by sight and captured with interception traps. 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, D. B." box="[362,535,1881,1907]" pageId="2" pageNumber="78" refId="ref9584" refString="Thomas, D. B. (1992) Taxonomic synopsis of the Asopine Pentatomidae (Heteroptera) of the Western Hemisphere. The Thomas Say Foundation Eds. Vol. XVI. The Entomological Society of America Publishers, Lanham, Maryland, 156 pp." type="book" year="1992">Thomas (1992)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned three color forms of this species: the typical metallic blue form, the orange-red, 
<emphasis box="[287,430,1917,1943]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="78">schumacheri</emphasis>
form, and the reddish with large yellow spots on the dorsum, 
<emphasis box="[1130,1258,1917,1943]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="78">mullenhoffi</emphasis>
form (
<figureCitation box="[1335,1422,1917,1943]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1695,1720]" captionTargetBox="[228,1360,171,1660]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[228,1360,166,1675]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus of Asopinae from French Guiana (except H. lepida). A.—Alcaeorrhynchus grandis (Dallas, 1851).— Remire-Montjoly, Lotissement Amaryllis, UV-MV light trap, ϐ 23.X.2011, SEAG leg. (coll. RL). B.—Coryzorhaphis carneolus Erichson, 1848.—Saint-Laurent-du-Maroni, Piste crique serpent pK19, ♀ VI.2001, Jean Cerda leg. (coll. RL). C.—Discocera cayennensis Laporte, 1833 mullenhoffi form—Roura, Montagne de Kaw pK37.5, hand catching, ϐ 6.V.2003, A. Bout leg. (coll. RL). D.—D. cayennensis emerald form—Roura, Montagne de Kaw pK38, hand catching, ♀ 22.V.2003, R. Lupoli leg. (coll. RL). E.—Discocera coccinea (Fabricius, 1798) ochrocyanea form.—Maripasoula, Mont Itoupé, FIT, ♀ 23.III.2010, SEAG leg. (coll. RL). F.—Heteroscelis bimaculata (Walker, 1867).—Régina, Nouragues, Inselberg, UV-MV light trap, ϐ 9. X.2012, SEAG leg. (coll. RL). G.—Heteroscelis lepida (Stål, 1862).—EL SALVADOR.—Guazapa, 10.IX.1959, J. Bechyné leg. (coll. IRSNB). H.—Heteroscelis servillei Laporte, 1833.—Mana, Réserve Trinité, DZ Aya, Malaise trap, ϐ 1.VI.2012, SEAG leg. (coll. RL). Photos R. Lupoli. Scale = 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3448997" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3448997/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="78">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
). The 
<emphasis box="[202,345,1953,1979]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="78">schumacheri</emphasis>
form was not observed in 
<collectingCountry box="[649,818,1953,1979]" name="French Guiana" pageId="2" pageNumber="78">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
, unlike both the metallic dark blue and the 
<emphasis box="[1309,1437,1953,1979]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="78">mullenhoffi</emphasis>
forms. We also observed a metallic emerald green form that we will name the 
<emphasis box="[1013,1105,1989,2015]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="78">emerald</emphasis>
form (
<figureCitation box="[1180,1269,1989,2015]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1695,1720]" captionTargetBox="[228,1360,171,1660]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[228,1360,166,1675]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus of Asopinae from French Guiana (except H. lepida). A.—Alcaeorrhynchus grandis (Dallas, 1851).— Remire-Montjoly, Lotissement Amaryllis, UV-MV light trap, ϐ 23.X.2011, SEAG leg. (coll. RL). B.—Coryzorhaphis carneolus Erichson, 1848.—Saint-Laurent-du-Maroni, Piste crique serpent pK19, ♀ VI.2001, Jean Cerda leg. (coll. RL). C.—Discocera cayennensis Laporte, 1833 mullenhoffi form—Roura, Montagne de Kaw pK37.5, hand catching, ϐ 6.V.2003, A. Bout leg. (coll. RL). D.—D. cayennensis emerald form—Roura, Montagne de Kaw pK38, hand catching, ♀ 22.V.2003, R. Lupoli leg. (coll. RL). E.—Discocera coccinea (Fabricius, 1798) ochrocyanea form.—Maripasoula, Mont Itoupé, FIT, ♀ 23.III.2010, SEAG leg. (coll. RL). F.—Heteroscelis bimaculata (Walker, 1867).—Régina, Nouragues, Inselberg, UV-MV light trap, ϐ 9. X.2012, SEAG leg. (coll. RL). G.—Heteroscelis lepida (Stål, 1862).—EL SALVADOR.—Guazapa, 10.IX.1959, J. Bechyné leg. (coll. IRSNB). H.—Heteroscelis servillei Laporte, 1833.—Mana, Réserve Trinité, DZ Aya, Malaise trap, ϐ 1.VI.2012, SEAG leg. (coll. RL). Photos R. Lupoli. Scale = 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3448997" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3448997/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="78">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
). All of the ob- served blue metallic and 
<emphasis box="[427,519,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="79">emerald</emphasis>
specimens are females and the 
<emphasis box="[868,996,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="79">mullenhoffi</emphasis>
specimens are males. A link could exist between the color patterns of this species and the adult forms of its larval preys, even if the colors of the larvae are not the same as the adults. We observed an emerald form predating on the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[986,1156,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysomelidae</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1807" box="[1163,1366,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aulica">
<emphasis box="[1163,1366,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="79">Platyphora aulica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
larva, and a 
<emphasis box="[223,351,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="79">mullenhoffi</emphasis>
form predating on the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[620,790,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysomelidae</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[799,924,262,287]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aestuans">
<emphasis box="[799,924,262,287]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="79">P. aestuans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
larva. The 
<emphasis box="[1058,1150,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="79">emerald</emphasis>
form has a similar color as the adults of 
<taxonomicName authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1807" box="[335,433,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aulica">
<emphasis box="[335,433,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="79">P. aulica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(except the head, orange in 
<taxonomicName authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1807" box="[762,859,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aulica">
<emphasis box="[762,859,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="79">P. aulica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The 
<emphasis box="[937,1065,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="79">mullenhoffi</emphasis>
form arrays a similar coloration pattern (11 yellow spots, reddish background) to the adults of 
<taxonomicName authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[851,977,334,359]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aestuans">
<emphasis box="[851,977,334,359]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="79">P. aestuans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(8 yellow spots, red background). These resemblances may be mimetic adaptations to take advantage of similarities against predators, and perhaps also to be able to approach surreptitiously the 
<taxonomicName authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" box="[560,686,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[560,686,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="79">Platyphora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
larvae preys as closely as possible since adults maternal care was observed in this genus (
<bibRefCitation author="Windsor, D. M. &amp; Dury, G. J. &amp; Frieiro-Costa, F. A. &amp; Lanckowsky, S. &amp; Pasteels, J. M." box="[415,650,441,467]" pageId="3" pageNumber="79" pagination="71 - 93" refId="ref9706" refString="Windsor, D. M., Dury, G. J., Frieiro-Costa, F. A., Lanckowsky, S. &amp; Pasteels, J. M. (2013) Subsocial Neotropical Doryphorini (Chrysomelidae, Chrysomelinae): new observations on behavior, host plants and systematics. ZooKeys, 332, 71 - 93. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 332.5199" type="journal article" year="2013">
Windsor 
<emphasis box="[519,569,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="79">et al</emphasis>
., 2013
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
